><H1
><A
NAME="COURIERPOP3D"
></A
>courierpop3d</H1
><DIV
CLASS="REFNAMEDIV"
><A
NAME="AEN10"
></A
><H2
>Name</H2
>courierpop3d&nbsp;--&nbsp;Courier POP3 server</DIV
><DIV
CLASS="REFSYNOPSISDIV"
><A
NAME="AEN13"
></A
><H2
>Synopsis</H2
><P
><B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>@sbindir@/couriertcpd</B
> {-nodnslookup} {-stderr=syslog} {110} {@libexecdir@/courier/courierpop3login} [<VAR
CLASS="REPLACEABLE"
>modules</VAR
>...] {@libexecdir@/courier/courierpop3d} {./Maildir}</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="REFSECT1"
><A
NAME="AEN24"
></A
><H2
>DESCRIPTION</H2
><P
>This is a simple POP3 server for Maildirs.</P
><DIV
CLASS="NOTE"
><P
></P
><TABLE
CLASS="NOTE"
WIDTH="100%"
BORDER="0"
><TR
><TD
WIDTH="25"
ALIGN="CENTER"
VALIGN="TOP"
>NOTE:</TD
><TD
ALIGN="LEFT"
VALIGN="TOP"
><P
>The <B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>couriertcpd</B
>, <B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>courierpop3login</B
>,
and <B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>courierpop3d</B
> modules may be installed elsewhere than
indicated here.</P
></TD
></TR
></TABLE
></DIV
><P
><B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>courierpop3login</B
> is usually started by
<B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>couriertcpd</B
>. It
already expects that a POP3 client is connected to standard input and output,
presumably via a network socket.
<B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>courierpop3login</B
> reads the POP3
userid and password, then runs the
authentication <TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>modules</TT
>. The remaining
arguments are passed along as arguments to <TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>modules</TT
>.</P
><P
><TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>modules</TT
>
is one or more authentication modules (see the
<A
HREF="authlib.html"
TARGET="_top"
><SPAN
CLASS="CITEREFENTRY"
><SPAN
CLASS="REFENTRYTITLE"
>authlib</SPAN
>(7)</SPAN
></A
>
manual page).</P
><P
>Each authentication modules runs the program specified by its first
argument, allowing the authentication modules to be chained. The last program
in the chain is
<B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>courierpop3d</B
>
, which provides the actual POP3 service. In
accordance with the authentication protocol, as described in
<A
HREF="authlib.html"
TARGET="_top"
><SPAN
CLASS="CITEREFENTRY"
><SPAN
CLASS="REFENTRYTITLE"
>authlib</SPAN
>(7)</SPAN
></A
>
<B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>courierpop3d</B
> reads
file descriptor 3 to see if the userid/password has been succesfully
validated. If not, <B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>courierpop3d</B
> terminates.</P
><P
>Otherwise, <B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>courierpop3d</B
> expects to be already running
under the
appropriate user and group id, with its current directory set to the account's
home directory.</P
><P
>The first order of business is to find the account's Maildir. If the
environment variable <VAR
CLASS="ENVAR"
>MAILDIR</VAR
> is set, that's where we go.
That should be the
pathname to the account's Maildir. The environment variable
<VAR
CLASS="ENVAR"
>MAILDIR</VAR
> may be set by the
authentication module.
If <VAR
CLASS="ENVAR"
>MAILDIR</VAR
> is not set,
<B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>courierpop3d</B
> uses its first argument.
Usually, the default maildir is
<TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>$HOME/Maildir</TT
>, therefore the first argument to
<B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>courierpop3d</B
> is
"<TT
CLASS="LITERAL"
>./Maildir</TT
>".</P
></DIV
